  abstract = {What are the risky choices people are confronted with in our complex and fast-changing world? This article reports on a set of representative population surveys in Switzerland (N = 4, 380) that collected those risky choices people perceive to be relevant in their own lives or in the lives of a large number of fellow citizens. Based on this empirical basis we developed an inventory of 100 risky choices, which we analyzed to address several open issues of the behavioral sciences, such as regarding the structure of the current ecology of risk (e.g., life domains; stability). Moreover, we employed this inventory with an independent follow-up study (N = 933) to thus address the generalizabilty of the psychological construct of risk preference to real-life choices that are relevant to various subgroups of the population. The five key insights that emerged from developing, analyzing, and employing this inventory may not only be useful for researchers studying decision making under risk and uncertainty (e.g., what criteria to use for the development of novel measurement instruments), but also for policy making and various applied settings (e.g., by mapping who will likely be confronted with which risky choices; how swiftly the risks of modern life change, either spontaneously or in response to a global shock).},
  langid = {english},
